actually save lives. I don't mean to compare what he did for a living to what

is more important, but Kobe was a hero in the way Superman is a hero. He was so big
it was almost like he was a fictional character. He was a real-life superhero
with a costume and everything walking amongst us. Those of us who love the
Lakers know it seemed like he always came through. He always showed up to save the
day. He wanted to save the day. He had a force of will. He never gave up. As an
athlete, he was incredibly gifted more than almost anyone. He was talented beyond
reason and yet he worked harder than everyone. He worked harder than people
with much less talent than he had. He took his job and his pursuit of excellence so
seriously. He was completely dedicated to being as good as he possibly could be
which is inspiring to anyone who does anything and we loved him because of
that, but we also loved him because he was ours. We watched him grow up here. He
came to LA when he was a teenager and unlike almost every other superstar
athlete, he never left. In his 20-year career, he only wore two uniforms for the
Lakers and for the United States Olympic team. There were times when it seemed
like he would leave, but he didn't. He stayed until the end and he's someone
almost everyone in this city loved and not just Lakers fans. Everyone would light
up when they saw him. I saw him many times. He was special. He was a special person, a
